definition.value: An amino cyclitol consisting of scyllo-inositol with the hydroxy groups at positions 1 and 3 replaced by unsubstituted amino groups.
A tropane alkaloid obtained from leaves of the South American shrub Erythroxylon coca.
A 3-hydroxy steroid that is estra-1,3,5(10)-trien-3-ol substituted by additional hydroxy groups at positions 16 and 17 (16alpha,17beta-stereoisomer).
A nitrile that is hydrogen cyanide in which the hydrogen has been replaced by a phenyl group.
An N-sulfonylurea that consists of 1-butylurea having a tosyl group attached at the 3-position.

A complex glycopeptide from Streptomyces orientalis. It inhibits a specific step in the synthesis of the peptidoglycan layer in the Gram-positive bacteria Staphylococcus aureus and Clostridium difficile.
The most important reserve polysaccharide found in plants. It is a glucan consisting of amylose and amylopectin.
A monohydroxyacetophenone carrying a hydroxy substituent at position 4'.
An aromatic amino acid that is alanine in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a phenyl group.

An N-sulfonylurea that is urea in which a hydrogen attached to one of the nitrogens is replaced by a p-acetylphenylsulfonyl group, while a hydrogen attached to the other nitrogen is replaced by a cyclohexyl group.
A glycosylglucose formed by an alpha-(1->6)-linkage between D-galactose and D-glucose.
A cresol that is phenol substituted by a methyl group at position 2. It is a minor urinary metabolite of toluene.

A polydisperse highly branched polysaccharide derivative composed of chains of D-glucopyranose residues in alpha(1->4) glycosidic linkage. The chains are joined together by alpha(1->6) glycosidic linkages. A small number of alpha(1->3) glycosidic linkages and some 6-phosphate ester groups also may occur. The branches in amylopectin typically contain 24 to 30 glucose residues.
A xylene substituted by methyl groups at positions 1 and 2.
A rutinoside consisting of cyanidin having the rutinosyl group at the 3-position.
A chromium group element atom that has atomic number 24.
A member of the class of rifamycins that is a a semisynthetic antibiotic derived from Amycolatopsis rifamycinica (previously known as Amycolatopsis mediterranei and Streptomyces mediterranei).
A monochlorophenol substituted at the pare position by a chlorine atom.
A bornane monoterpenoid that is 1,7,7-trimethylbicyclo[2.2.1]heptane substituted by a hydroxy group at position 2.

A glucan composed of unbranched chains of D-glucopyranose residues in alpha(1->4) glycosidic linkage. The number of repeated glucose subunits (n) is usually in the range of 300 to 3000, but can be many thousands. One of the two components of starch (the other, 70-80%, being amylopectin). Cf. linear maltodextrin, in which the chain length is typically between 3 and 17 glucose units.
The conjugate base of loracarbef.
A member of the class of ethanolamines that is ethanolamine having a N-hydroxyethyl substituent.
A docosahexaenoic acid having six cis-double bonds at positions 4, 7, 10, 13, 16 and 19.

A D-gluconate adduct of indefinite composition containing between 30 and 34% of antimony(V), calculated with reference to dried and methanol-free substance. It is used as a treatment for leishmaniasis.
An optically active form of asparagine having D-configuration.
A tryptophan derivative that is tryptophan substituted by a hydroxy group at position 5.
A dimethylxanthine having the two methyl groups located at positions 1 and 3. It is structurally similar to caffeine and is found in green and black tea.
An aromatic amide that consists of benzene bearing a single carboxamido substituent. The parent of the class of benzamides.
The D-enantiomer of leucine.
A trihydroxyflavanone having the three hydroxy gropus located at the 3'-, 5- and 7-positions and an additional methoxy substituent at the 4'-position.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of dichloroacetic acid.
A benzylisoquinoline alkaloid that is isoquinoline substituted by methoxy groups at positions 6 and 7 and a 3,4-dimethoxybenzyl group at position 1. It has been isolated from Papaver somniferum.
An ultra-long-chain primary fatty alcohol that is octacosane in which a hydrogen attached to one of the terminal carbons is replaced by a hydroxy group.
An aldohexose that is the C-4 epimer of glucose.
A 2-carbon sulfoxide in which the sulfur atom has two methyl substituents.
An ortho-fused tricyclic hydrocarbon that is a major component of fossil fuels and their derivatives
An alpha-amino acid that consists of butyric acid bearing an amino substituent at position 2 and a carbamoyl substituent at position 4.

A highly sulfated linear glycosaminoglycan comprising complex patterns of uronic acid-(1->4)-D-glucosamine repeating subunits. Used as an injectable anticoagulant, it has the highest negative charge density of any known biological molecule.
A monocarboxylic acid amide that is urea where one of the amino groups has been replaced with hydrazine.

7H-Furo[3,2-g]chromen-7-one in which positions 2, 5, and 9 are substituted by methyl groups. Like other psoralens, trioxsalen causes photosensitization of the skin. It is administered orally in conjunction with UV-A for phototherapy treatment of vitiligo. After photoactivation it creates interstrand cross-links in DNA, inhibiting DNA synthesis and cell division, and can lead to cell injury; recovery from the cell injury may be followed by increased melanisation of the epidermis.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-lactic acid.
An icosapentaenoic acid having five cis-double bonds at positions 5, 8, 11, 14 and 17.
